Rust offers different ways to initialize compile time-initialized variables. Recently, I had to create a runtime-initialized variable: existing approaches don't work in this case. I want to describe multiple ways to achieve it in this post. The Rust language allows you to create constants. Two keywords are available: const and static. Sometimes a certain value is used many times throughout a program, and it can become inconvenient to copy it over and over. What‚Äôs more, it‚Äôs not always possible or desirable to make it a variable that gets carried around to each function that needs it. In these cases, the const keyword provides a convenient alternative to code duplication: const THING: u32 = 0xABAD1DEA;
let foo = 123 + THING;
